A [3ct D-IF lab grown emerald cut diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) from certified market inventory is currently [**$9,235**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The closest natural equivalent — a [GIA 3ct F-VS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/15813280?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — is [**$63,574**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/15813280?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Same carbon. Same IGI or GIA certificate. Same grade. $54,339 difference.

That gap is bigger for the emerald cut than for any other diamond shape. The reason has to do with how this shape is built — and once you understand it, buying a natural emerald cut diamond feels like paying full sticker price when there is a sign on the door that says 85% off.

This post covers prices from [2ct through 5ct lab grown emerald cuts](/lab-grown-emerald-cut-diamond), the clarity grades that actually matter on a step-cut table, how lab compares to moissanite in this specific shape, and the one price inversion in the data that most buyers miss completely.

---

**TL;DR**

The single most important insight: a lab grown emerald cut at 3ct D-IF costs [**$9,235**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) vs $63,574 natural — 85% less for the same grade.

→ Start at [2ct D-FL IGI at **$4,735**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28828463?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) if you want the clearest entry point. Step up to [3ct D-IF at **$9,235**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) if you want a stone people will notice. For buyers who want sheer size, [4ct D-VVS1 at **$7,737**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs less than the 2ct natural equivalent — that is the inversion this post is built around.

Priority: buy lab. For the emerald cut specifically, this is not a close call.

---

## The Open Table Paradox

Every other popular diamond shape hides what's inside it. A round brilliant has 57–58 facets working constantly — scattering light, creating motion, masking the interior. An oval does the same. A cushion scatters even more. When a gem cutter designs a round diamond, inclusions that sit near the table get broken up by reflected light before your eye can settle on them.

The emerald cut does the opposite. It has a broad, flat rectangular table — sometimes 60–65% of the total width — and long step facets that run parallel to the girdle. Instead of scattering light, those facets reflect it in straight, clean bands. The result is what jewelers call the "hall of mirrors" effect: deep rectangular reflections that stack inside each other like a corridor of glass. It is the most architecturally structured look in diamond cutting.

But those same straight reflections that make the emerald cut beautiful also make it honest. When you look down through that open table, you are looking directly into the stone. There is no facet geometry to interrupt the view. An SI1 inclusion that hides in a round brilliant shows clearly in an emerald cut. A VS2 that looks clean in an oval can face up noticeably in a step cut. Gem labs and jewelers have known this for decades — it is why H-I/SI1 earrings in bezel prong styles grade the same as VS2 in solitaire rings when viewed face-up.

This is the Open Table Paradox: the shape that requires the highest clarity grade also happens to be the shape where lab diamonds' advantage is most extreme. Lab grown diamonds are produced under controlled conditions — CVD (chemical vapor deposition) or HPHT (high pressure, high temperature) growth — and the types of inclusions they form are different from natural diamonds. Natural diamonds develop under millions of years of geological pressure, creating feather fractures, crystal inclusions, and cloud formations. Lab grown stones develop under monitored conditions and tend toward fewer of the feather and cloud inclusion types that are most visible under step-cut faceting.

The result: a lab grown emerald cut at VS1 or VVS1 has genuinely cleaner face-up appearance than a natural at the same grade. The open table amplifies the lab advantage rather than hiding it.

![Lab grown emerald cut diamond clarity comparison — how the step-cut table reveals inclusions vs round brilliant](/images/lab-grown-emerald-cut-diamond-clarity-guide.avif)

> "The emerald cut is the shape where I tell everyone to buy lab. When you're looking down through that open table, clarity isn't optional — it's everything. And the price difference between natural VS1 and lab VS1 is so extreme that anyone paying natural prices for an emerald cut is leaving real money behind."
>
> — Farzana, DiamondCritics

