## The 4ct Inversion

This is the data point most lab diamond guides never catch. Look at the 4ct vs 3ct lab price again.

A [3ct D-IF lab](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs [**$9,235**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). A [4ct D-VVS1 lab](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs [**$7,737**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). You can buy a larger stone at a lower clarity grade for less money. And that [4ct D-VVS1 at $7,737](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is also cheaper than the [natural 2ct F-VS1 at $24,407](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/14013191?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

This is not a data error. It is a real structural feature of the lab diamond market — and it exists right now because of how lab diamond production scales.

Growing a 4ct emerald cut diamond in a lab takes longer than growing a 2ct, but the marginal production cost does not scale at the same rate as value. At 3ct, stones are graded D-IF in the open market and buyers expect to pay accordingly. At 4ct D-VVS1, the VVS1 instead of IF/FL creates a different buyer pool and price tier. The D-VVS1 4ct is still an extraordinary stone — in an emerald cut, the visual difference between VVS1 and IF under the open table is essentially zero unless you have a loupe and know exactly where to look.

What you can actually see in the step-cut window: D color is completely colorless. VVS1 has inclusions so small they are invisible to the naked eye and difficult to find even at 10x magnification. You will never see the difference between VVS1 and FL in this stone face-up. You will pay [double for the FL grade](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29327214?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — [$16,428 vs $7,737](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — and see nothing different in the mirror.

The inversion is even more dramatic at 5ct. A [5ct E-VVS1 lab](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28857918?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is [**$8,210**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28857918?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). A [natural 2ct F-VS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/14013191?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is [**$24,407**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/14013191?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). You get 5 carats of lab for less than what a 2ct natural costs. This is the 4ct Inversion extended — and the emerald cut is the only shape where the face-up size difference between 2ct and 5ct is this visually dramatic.

Why the emerald cut specifically? Because of how size reads on this shape. An emerald cut has a large table coverage relative to its carat weight compared to rounds or ovals. A 5ct emerald cut faces up wider than a 5ct round. The open flat table exaggerates the visual size advantage. When The 4ct Inversion lets you buy 4–5ct lab for less than the price of 2ct natural, the emerald cut is the shape where that size upgrade is most visible.

