## What Clarity Grade to Choose for a Lab Grown Emerald Cut

This is the question most buyers get wrong. They see D-FL available at [2ct for $3,862](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29396015?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and assume FL is the right choice. It is often not — and understanding why requires knowing what you actually see through an emerald cut's open table.

**What each clarity grade looks like face-up in a lab grown emerald cut:**

**FL (Flawless):** No inclusions or surface blemishes at 10x magnification. Face-up appearance is identical to VVS1. The only person who can tell the difference is a gemologist with a loupe looking for something to find. You pay a premium for a certificate notation that your eye cannot confirm.

**IF (Internally Flawless):** No internal inclusions. May have minor surface blemishes. Face-up identical to VVS1 under normal viewing. This is the grade in the [3ct D-IF at $9,235](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — it is exceptional value because IF in a lab stone does not carry the same rarity premium as natural IF.

**VVS1/VVS2 (Very Very Slightly Included):** Inclusions are present but essentially impossible to see with the naked eye. Even under 10x loupe, finding them requires effort. For the emerald cut's open table, VVS1 is completely eye-clean. The [2ct D-VVS1 at $5,335](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29639473?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the [4ct D-VVS1 at $7,737](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) are both excellent choices.

**VS1/VS2 (Very Slightly Included):** VS1 is consistently eye-clean in lab grown emerald cuts. VS2 requires inspection — in an emerald cut specifically, some VS2 stones have inclusions that sit near the center of the table and catch light through the step facets. Always ask to see VS2 stones before buying. In a natural emerald cut, gemologists often recommend VS2 as the minimum safe grade. In lab grown, the inclusion character is different enough that VS1 is the safer floor.

**SI1/SI2 (Slightly Included):** Not recommended for the emerald cut — in any context, lab or natural. The open table will show SI1 inclusions that would be invisible in a round. SI1 and SI2 are acceptable in rounds and ovals. They are not appropriate for step cuts.

**The practical recommendation:** Buy VVS1 or better. The [4ct D-VVS1 at $7,737](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the sweet spot of the entire dataset — exceptional size, D color, and completely clean face-up appearance, at a price that inverts the natural 2ct market.

