**Setting choice for lab grown emerald cut:** The bezel is the right setting for this stone. Prong settings on an emerald cut place metal at the four corners of the rectangular table — those prongs cast shadows that interrupt the clean step-facet reflections. The bezel wraps around the edge without touching the table face. You get a cleaner view of the hall-of-mirrors effect, corner protection (the emerald cut's sharp corners are vulnerable to chipping), and no metal in the sightlines.

**Total ring cost examples:** Pair the [3ct D-IF lab stone at $9,235](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) with the [bezel white gold setting at $4,300](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/bezel-set-emerald-cut-side-stone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-304632?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and your total ring is approximately $13,535. A natural 3ct emerald cut in any comparable setting starts above $70,000.

For the [4ct D-VVS1 at $7,737](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) plus the [platinum bezel at $4,625](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/bezel-set-emerald-cut-side-stone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-304637?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), total is approximately $12,362. A 4ct emerald cut ring in natural starts at over $100,000.

> "When I show someone the 4ct lab next to the 4ct natural price, they always assume there must be a quality catch. There isn't. The catch is that one grew over a billion years in the earth and one grew in a controlled facility over a few weeks. Both are carbon. Both are graded by the same certification bodies. The step-cut table does not know the difference."
>
> — Farzana, DiamondCritics

