## Moissanite vs Emerald Cut Lab Diamond

The [emerald cut moissanite vs diamond](/emerald-cut-diamond-engagement-rings) question comes up constantly. Here is the honest answer.

Moissanite is silicon carbide. Diamond — lab or natural — is carbon. They are different minerals with different optical properties. The price gap is real: a 2ct emerald cut moissanite (Forever One or equivalent) runs roughly $350–600. A [2ct lab D-FL emerald cut diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28828463?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is [$4,735](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28828463?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). That is a $4,100+ difference.

**Where moissanite and lab diamond actually differ in the emerald cut:**

The step-cut format is the one shape where the optical difference between moissanite and diamond is most visible. Here is why. Moissanite has higher fire (dispersion) than diamond — it scatters more colored light. In a brilliant cut, that reads as extra sparkle. In an emerald cut, where light travels through flat rectangular windows in straight bands, moissanite's higher dispersion creates colored flashes inside those reflections. You see more rainbow. Diamond's fire in the emerald cut is quieter — white flashes in the step facets, not colored ones. The hall-of-mirrors effect reads as cooler, more architectural, more glassy.

Whether that is better or worse depends on what you like. But the difference is there, and the emerald cut is where it is most visible. In rounds, ovals, and cushions — the brilliant-cut shapes — moissanite's extra fire blends in. Under the flat step-cut table, it stands out.

**The certification gap:** Diamond, lab or natural, receives GIA, IGI, or GCAL certification. Moissanite does not receive diamond grading reports because it is not a diamond. If certification matters to you — for insurance, resale, or documentation — only diamond gets graded.

**The resale reality:** Lab diamonds currently hold limited resale value — significantly less than natural. Moissanite holds essentially no resale value. Neither is a financial asset. If you are buying jewelry as an investment, neither is appropriate. If you are buying jewelry to wear and love, both are legitimate choices — and lab diamond gives you a certified, graded stone.

