## Lab Grown Emerald Cut Diamond: The Certification Question

About 70% of lab grown emerald cut diamonds at 2ct and above in certified inventory are graded by IGI or GCAL — not GIA. This is not a red flag. It is a market reality.

GIA began issuing comprehensive cut-grade reports for lab diamonds in 2023. Before that, their lab diamond reports did not include cut grades. IGI and GCAL have been grading lab diamonds with full cut assessments for longer. So the IGI-graded stone you see at 3ct D-IF has been evaluated for its cut, color, clarity, and carat weight the same way any GIA stone is — by a different but reputable independent lab.

**When GIA matters more:** For natural emerald cut diamonds, GIA is the gold standard and its reports carry more market confidence. For lab diamonds specifically, the premium you pay for a GIA report over IGI at the same grade is often 20–40%. For an emerald cut, where cut grading is less standardized than rounds anyway, that premium is harder to justify.

**The cut grade wrinkle:** GIA and IGI use different cut grade systems for fancy shapes. Emerald cuts are step cuts with no universal "Ideal" cut standard the way rounds have. The proportions that produce the best hall-of-mirrors effect (roughly 60–65% table, 58–64% depth, 1.30–1.50 length-to-width ratio) are not enforced by any certification. You have to look at the measurements yourself, not just the cut grade. An IGI "Ideal Cut" with good proportions beats a GIA "Excellent" with poor depth any day.

**What to look for beyond the certificate:**
- Length-to-width ratio: 1.30–1.50 for classic emerald cut. Below 1.30 looks nearly square. Above 1.55 looks very elongated.
- Table percentage: 60–66%. Too high and the stone looks flat. Too low and the hall-of-mirrors effect becomes compressed.
- Depth: 58–66%. Too shallow and the stone is lifeless. Too deep and you lose face-up size.
- No visible inclusions at 10x loupe in the center of the table — this is where they will show most.

