## Final Verdict

**Best overall pick:** [3ct D-IF IGI lab at **$9,235**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Three carats is substantial face-up presence in an emerald cut. D-IF is the highest possible grade combination. And $9,235 is less than some people spend on a 0.5ct natural emerald cut in the same clarity bracket. Set in a bezel and this is a ring that will stop conversations.

**Best size-per-dollar pick:** [4ct D-VVS1 IGI lab at **$7,737**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Less money than the 3ct D-IF. More stone. VVS1 is completely eye-clean in a step cut. The only reason to choose the 3ct D-IF over this is if the IF certificate matters to you specifically.

**Best statement pick:** [5ct E-VVS1 IGI lab at **$8,210**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28857918?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Five carats in an emerald cut is a full-finger stone. E color is essentially colorless. VVS1 is eye-clean. And $8,210 is less than the natural 2ct equivalent. If presence is what you want and you are not chasing a certificate notation for its own sake, this is the pick.

**Best entry pick:** [1.94ct F-VVS1 IGI lab at **$2,229**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29147824?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Under $2,500 for a nearly-2ct F-VVS1 certified emerald cut. If this budget range works for you, this is an exceptional stone. F color is near-colorless. VVS1 is fully eye-clean. The face-up appearance is indistinguishable from a D-FL at arm's length.

