## FAQ

### What is a lab grown emerald cut diamond?

A lab grown emerald cut diamond is a real diamond — carbon atoms in a crystalline structure — grown in a controlled laboratory environment using CVD (chemical vapor deposition) or HPHT (high pressure, high temperature) methods. The emerald cut is a step-cut shape with a broad rectangular table and parallel step facets. It is graded by the same certification bodies (GIA, IGI, GCAL) using the same 4C standards as natural diamonds.

### How much does a 2 carat lab grown emerald cut diamond cost?

A 2 carat lab grown emerald cut diamond ranges from [**$2,229**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29147824?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for an F-VVS1 IGI to [**$5,335**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29639473?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for a D-VVS1 GCAL, depending on grade and certification. A natural 2ct F-VS1 comparison stone is [$24,407](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/14013191?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Lab saves 77–91% at this size.

### How much does a 3 carat lab grown emerald cut diamond cost?

A 3 carat lab grown emerald cut diamond is [**$9,235**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for a D-IF IGI to [**$10,695**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29354702?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for a D-VVS1 GCAL from certified market inventory. The equivalent natural 3ct F-VS1 is [$63,574](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/15813280?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — 85% more.

### How much does a 4 carat lab grown emerald cut diamond cost?

A 4 carat lab grown emerald cut diamond D-VVS1 is [**$7,737**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — less than the 3ct D-IF. That is the price inversion. A D-FL 4ct lab runs [$16,428–$17,315](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29327214?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The natural 4ct G-VS1 comparison is [$97,688](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/20429165?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

### How much does a 5 carat lab grown emerald cut diamond cost?

A 5 carat lab grown emerald cut diamond starts at [**$8,210**](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28857918?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for an E-VVS1 IGI and goes up to [$19,871](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27428837?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for a D-FL GCAL. The natural 5ct D-VS1 equivalent is [$121,475](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/16360919?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). At 5ct, lab saves 93%.

### Is a lab grown emerald cut diamond real?

Yes. A lab grown diamond is chemically, physically, and optically identical to a natural diamond. Both are carbon in a crystalline lattice structure. The difference is origin — one grew underground over billions of years, one grew in a controlled facility over weeks. GIA, IGI, and GCAL certify both using the same 4C grading standards.

### What clarity grade should I buy for a lab grown emerald cut diamond?

Buy VS1 or better. VVS1 is ideal. The emerald cut's open rectangular table reveals inclusions that other shapes hide under facet geometry. SI1 and SI2 inclusions that are invisible in a round or oval can be visible face-up in an emerald cut. VS1 is the practical minimum for a clean appearance. The [4ct D-VVS1 at $7,737](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29587315?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the best clarity-per-dollar stone in the dataset.

### Is IGI or GIA better for a lab grown emerald cut diamond?

Both are reputable certifications. IGI has been grading lab diamonds with full cut assessments longer than GIA. For lab diamonds specifically, GIA-certified stones often command a 20–40% premium over IGI at the same grade. For an emerald cut — where cut grading is less standardized than rounds — that premium is difficult to justify. IGI-certified [3ct D-IF at $9,235](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) represents better value than paying a 30% premium for GIA paper on a stone with the same optical properties.

### What setting works best for a lab grown emerald cut diamond ring?

A bezel setting. Prong settings on an emerald cut place metal at the four corners of the table, casting shadows that interrupt the step-facet light reflections. The bezel wraps the edge without touching the face, giving you a clean view of the hall-of-mirrors effect, corner protection, and no prong shadows. See the [bezel settings above](#lab-grown-emerald-cut-diamond-ring-settings) starting at [$4,300](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/bezel-set-emerald-cut-side-stone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-304632?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

### What is the ideal length-to-width ratio for a lab grown emerald cut diamond?

1.30–1.50 is the standard range for a classic emerald cut look. Below 1.30 approaches a square (Asscher territory). Above 1.55 gets very elongated. Most buyers prefer 1.35–1.45 for the balanced rectangular silhouette. Check the stone's measurements — certification reports list both dimensions so you can calculate the ratio.

### Can you tell a lab grown from a natural emerald cut diamond?

Not by looking. Not with a loupe. Not with a standard diamond tester (both conduct heat the same way). The only way to identify a lab grown diamond is with specialized spectroscopic equipment that detects microscopic differences in crystal growth patterns — equipment only gem labs own. When you look at a lab emerald cut in a setting, you see the same D color, the same VVS1 clarity, the same hall-of-mirrors reflections as a natural at the same grade.

### Does a lab grown emerald cut diamond hold its value?

Lab grown diamonds currently hold less resale value than natural diamonds. The market for secondhand lab diamonds is still developing and prices have declined as production scaled. If resale value matters, natural diamonds are better positioned long-term — but even natural diamonds typically resell at 20–50% of retail. If you are buying jewelry to wear and love rather than as a financial asset, lab grown gives you a certified, graded diamond at 80–93% less than natural.

### What is the best lab grown emerald cut diamond for an engagement ring?

For most engagement ring buyers, the [3ct D-IF IGI at $9,235](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28885081?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) paired with a [bezel setting at $4,300](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/bezel-set-emerald-cut-side-stone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-304632?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — total approximately $13,500 — is the best combination of size, clarity, and budget. If total budget is under $10,000 for stone and setting, the [2ct D-FL at $4,735](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28828463?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the entry statement.

